BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:On February 13\, art and art history professor Maggie Cao (FFP 
 ’19) will give a lecture. The lecture is titled "Diurnal Medium: Early Phot
 ography in the Arctic."\n\nBuilding on research from her recently published
  book\, Painting US Empire: Nineteenth-Century Art and its Legacies\, which
  examines Arctic landscapes in one of its chapters\, Cao turns to another m
 edium used to depict Arctic expeditions: photography. British and American 
 explorers brought cameras to the Arctic soon after photography’s invention 
 in 1839 despite the requirement of traveling with cumbersome cameras\, vola
 tile chemicals\, and portable dark rooms. Light\, for capturing the image\,
  and darkness\, for developing it\, were essential conditions of photograph
 y\, making it a “diurnal” medium unlike other forms of representation. This
  talk considers the conundrum of making “sun pictures” (a period term for p
 hotography) of such phenomena as the midnight sun and perpetual night in a 
 geographical space beyond diurnal temporality.\n\nMaggie Cao is a scholar o
 f eighteenth and nineteenth-century American art in a global context. At UN
 C\, she teaches the history of American art from the colonial period to the
  twentieth century as well as courses on the visual histories of science an
 d economics. She is the author of two books: The End of Landscape in Ninete
 enth-Century America (University of California Press\, 2018)\, which examin
 es the dissolution of landscape painting as a major cultural project in the
  late nineteenth-century United States\, and Painting US Empire: Nineteenth
 -Century Art and its Legacies (Chicago University Press\, 2025)\, the first
  synthetic treatment of nineteenth-century art and empire in the global con
 text. Professor Cao is currently engaged in research on nineteenth-century 
 artistic engagements with ecological temporalities—the nonhuman time preser
 ved in tree rings\, ice cores\, and rock strata. Professor Cao received her
  doctorate in art history from Harvard University in 2014 and did postdocto
 ral work at Columbia University’s Society of Fellows before coming to UNC i
 n 2016. She has received fellowships for her research from the National Hum
 anities Center\, the Terra Foundation\, and the Smithsonian\, and the Getty
  Research Institute.\n\n \n\nSee all events in the IAH Fellows Forum series
 . Learn more about the Feb. 13 event at the IAH website.
DTEND:20260213T183000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215834Z
DTSTART:20260213T170000Z
GEO:35.913407;-79.052875
LOCATION:Hyde Hall\, 109 (University Room)
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:IAH Fellows Forum: Diurnal Medium: Early Photography in the Arctic
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51772094070104
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/iah-fellows-forum-diurnal-medium-early-p
 hotography-in-the-arctic
END:VEVENT
