CATEGORIES:Service
DESCRIPTION:When working in a historically underserved community\, it can b
 e easy to focus on what collective needs go unmet\, what resources are unav
 ailable\, and the hardships people experience on a daily basis. But how doe
 s this focus affect your attitude\, your approach to dialogue and collabora
 tion\, and your strategy development? Explore this question with the Marian
  Cheek Jackson Center\, a hub of creative action for Chapel Hill and Carrbo
 ro’s historically Black neighborhoods.\n\nThe Abundance-based Community Dev
 elopment workshop invites you to think about rhetorical and strategic frame
 works in the context of community empowerment. Read varying narratives of t
 he Northside neighborhood\, considering what kind of rhetoric moves you to 
 work creatively. Listen to local\, Black oral histories and notice the ways
  they affect you. Imagine the impact of building relationships and upliftin
 g your community’s existing power.\n\nPresenter(s): \n\nRenna Voss\, Studen
 t Engagement and Food Justice Fellow\, The Marian Cheek Jackson Center for 
 Saving and Making HistoryRegister HERE to attend. https://uncch.givepulse.c
 om/event/822674\n\n \n\nTo view other Carolina Engagement Week events\, vis
 it our website. Carolina Engagement Week is co-hosted by Carolina Across 10
 0\, the Carolina Center for Public Service\, the Carolina Engagement Counci
 l\, the Center for Thriving Communities\, NCGrowth\, ncIMPACT and UNC Rural
 .
