BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshops and Classes
DESCRIPTION:Grief is often linked to death\, but many of life’s losses are 
 quieter and less visible—changes in identity\, shifting roles\, unmet expec
 tations\, and transitions that leave lasting marks. Led jointly by a facult
 y researcher and a campus chaplain\, this seminar explores grief as a share
 d human experience\, drawing on research-based insights alongside reflectiv
 e and compassionate practices. Participants will examine how grief shapes i
 dentity\, relationships\, and sense of purpose\, while learning practical w
 ays to navigate loss in their own lives. The session will also consider how
  individuals and communities can create space for grief in supportive\, mea
 ningful ways. Participants will leave with concrete tools for honoring loss
 \, fostering resilience\, and sustaining compassion and continuity through 
 periods of change.
DTEND:20260226T183000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215834Z
DTSTART:20260226T170000Z
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Mental Health Seminar: From Grief to Growth - Navigating Loss with 
 Compassion and Strength
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51915436015980
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/mental-health-seminar-from-grief-to-grow
 th-navigating-loss-with-compassion-and-strength
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshops and Classes,Lectures
DESCRIPTION:Grief is often associated with death\, but loss takes many form
 s—shifts in identity\, changing roles\, unmet expectations\, and the quiet 
 disappointments that shape our lives. Led jointly by a faculty member and a
  campus chaplain\, this session integrates research-based insights with ref
 lective and compassionate practices.   \n\nDesigned to support both persona
 l reflection and broader community impact\, the seminar will offer practica
 l tools for navigating grief individually and strategies for integrating th
 ese concepts into community spaces. Participants will examine how grief inf
 luences identity\, relationships\, and sense of purpose\, while considering
  how individuals can honor what has been lost while remaining open to growt
 h and change. You will leave with a deeper understanding of grief as a shar
 ed human experience—and with approaches for fostering compassion\, resilien
 ce\, and continuity in times of change.
DTEND:20260226T183000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215834Z
DTSTART:20260226T170000Z
