BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:The Abbey Speaker Series marks the 250th anniversary of America
 n independence with a discussion of Race and the American Founding at 5:30p
 m on Thursday\, February 26 in the Frank Porter Graham Student Union Audito
 rium.\n\nThe Declaration of Independence proclaimed equality —”all men are 
 created equal”—but the Constitution tolerated slavery. Abolitionists\, Abra
 ham Lincoln\, and civil rights leaders later wielded the Declaration’s word
 s\, but its principal author\, Thomas Jefferson\, owned slaves\, and the De
 claration refers to Native Americans as “merciless savages.” How should we 
 think about this founding paradox that has haunted the nation for 250 years
 ? Historian Annette Gordon-Reed and political theorist Lucas Morel will exp
 lore these and related issues in a discussion moderated by Carolina Public 
 Humanities Executive Director Max Owre.\n\nStudents who attend in person ca
 n earn CLE credit. No tickets necessary\; seating is first-come\, first-ser
 ved. Reserved tickets are available for guests coming from outside Chapel H
 ill\; email publicdiscourse@unc.edu to reserve seats.\n\nJoin us for pizza 
 in the lobby afterward!
DTEND:20260227T000000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215834Z
DTSTART:20260226T223000Z
LOCATION:Frank Porter Graham Student Union Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Abbey Speaker Series: Race and the American Founding
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51223838973955
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/abbey-speaker-series-race-and-the-americ
 an-founding
END:VEVENT
