BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:Stéphane Gerson will deliver the Institute for the Arts and Hum
 anities Mary Stevens Reckford Memorial Lecture in European Studies on March
  5\, 2026.\n\n \n\nGerson\, a professor at New York University will recount
  his research into personal family history in a lecture titled\, “The Polit
 ics of Our Family Stories: Brussels\, 1994 - Nice\, 1942.”\n\nAs growing nu
 mbers of scholars write personal family histories\, this talk will reckon w
 ith the politics of this genre. How do we turn family stories into historic
 al objects\, open to their manifold dimensions and politics? How do we both
  honor and resist their narrative frameworks\, their silences and absences?
  Stéphane Gerson will address these questions by revisiting the story his g
 randmother Zosia told about her survival in Nazi-occupied Belgium and Franc
 e. Having heard this story as a child\, having videotaped it as a graduate 
 student (in 1994)\, he is now writing a historical ethnography of this wart
 ime adventure\, attuned to the multiple lives\, the multiple relationships 
 that unfold in its recesses. Which raises a final question: How\, beyond bi
 ological filiation but attuned to kinship\, do we write strangers as well a
 s relatives into existence?\n\n \n\nGerson is a professor of French\, Frenc
 h studies\, and history at New York University\, where he directed the Inst
 itute of French Studies for several years. His current research revolves ar
 ound personal family history and modes of historical writing\, especially a
 s it pertains to the Holocaust in Belgium and France. He recently edited an
  essay collection\, Scholars and Their Kin: Historical Explorations\, Liter
 ary Experiments (Chicago\, 2025) and is writing a historical ethnography of
  a family story: Les gestes de notre guerre\, 1994-1942 (La Découverte\, fo
 rthcoming).\n\n \n\nStudents may RSVP on Heel Life. This event is eligible 
 for CLE credit.\n\nRSVP for the 2026 Reckford Lecture on Jotform.\n\n \n\nT
 he Reckford Lecture\, which is co-sponsored by the Center for European Stud
 ies\, is hosted annually by the Institute for the Arts and Humanities. It w
 as established in 1990 by UNC classics professor Kenneth J. Reckford to hon
 or his wife\, Mary Stevens Reckford.
DTEND:20260305T223000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215834Z
DTSTART:20260305T210000Z
GEO:35.913407;-79.052875
LOCATION:Hyde Hall\, University Room (#109)
SEQUENCE:0
