BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Media Law and Policy organizes and hosts the Wad
 e H. Hargrove Media Law and Policy Colloquium. The colloquium was establish
 ed in 2009 to honor Wade Hargrove\, a graduate of the University of North C
 arolina at Chapel Hill and the UNC School of Law\, and to provide a forum f
 or the discussion of media law and media policy issues. It was funded in pa
 rt by Hearst Communications\, the North Carolina Association of Broadcaster
 s\, and the North Carolina Cable Telecommunications Association to recogniz
 e the more than 30 years of service that Mr. Hargrove provided to these org
 anizations as well as media and technology companies throughout North Carol
 ina and the nation.\n\n \n\nThis year's speaker is Kevin Martin. Kevin Mart
 in is the vice president and head of global policy at Meta where he oversee
 s Meta's global work with policymakers on privacy\, connectivity\, trade\, 
 and other issues. Previously\, he served as Meta's VP for U.S. Public Polic
 y and chairman (2005-2009) and commissioner (2001-2005) of the Federal Comm
 unications Commission. After leaving the FCC\, he joined the Aspen Institut
 e as a senior fellow at the think tank's Communications and Society Program
 \, and later the law firm Squire Patton Boggs LLP as a partner. He holds a 
 B.A. from the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill\, an M.P.P. from 
 Duke University\, and a J.D. from Harvard Law School.
DTEND:20260407T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215835Z
DTSTART:20260406T230000Z
GEO:35.912385;-79.004586
LOCATION:Rizzo Center
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:2026 Wade H. Hargrove Media Law and Policy Colloquium
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52266867374495
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/2026-wade-h-hargrove-media-law-and-polic
 y-colloquium
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Lectures
DESCRIPTION:The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill School of Socia
 l Work is pleased to welcome Maxine Eichner as the guest speaker for the 20
 26 annual Bobby Boyd Leadership Lecture Series on April 7\, 2026.\n\n \n\nE
 ichner’s lecture examines how the United States came to expect so much of f
 amilies with so little public support\, and how this gap has led overwhelmi
 ng numbers of poor and disproportionately Black families to be trapped in t
 he nation’s child welfare system. She traces how policy has come to emphasi
 ze family responsibility without parallel investment in the conditions that
  make children’s welfare truly possible\, while calling to build systems th
 at meet families earlier and to align policy with what children and familie
 s need to flourish.\n\n \n\nEichner is the Graham Kenan Distinguished Profe
 ssor of Law at UNC School of Law. She is both a lawyer and political scient
 ist. She writes on issues of families and inequality\; U.S. social welfare 
 law and policy\; and the relationship of the family\, the workplace\, and m
 arket forces. She is the author of The Free-Market Family: How the Market C
 rushed the American Dream (and How It Can Be Restored) (OUP\, 2020)\, and T
 he Supportive State: Families\, Government\, and America’s Political Ideals
  (OUP\, 2010).\n\n \n\nThis event will be presented virtually and in person
  in the auditorium of the Tate-Turner-Kuralt Building on UNC’s campus. The 
 presentation starts at 12:30 p.m. and is free and open to the public. Parti
 cipants are required to register for the event. A free lunch will be held i
 n the TTK lobby for attendees beginning at 11:30 a.m.
DTEND:20260407T174500Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215835Z
DTSTART:20260407T163000Z
GEO:35.907102;-79.054247
LOCATION:Tate-Turner-Kuralt Building\, Auditorium
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:2026 Bobby Boyd Leadership Lecture
