BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Exhibits,Lectures,Tours
DESCRIPTION:Join us on February 5th at 6:30PM in the Brown Gallery & Museum
  at the Stone Center for our Spring Exhibition Opening with Peabody Award-w
 inning journalist and photographer\, Brian Palmer.\n\nRSVP\n\nBrian palmer 
 is a Peabody award–winning journalist based in Richmond\, Virginia. During 
 his 30-year career he has photographed conflict\, politics\, activism\, dai
 ly life\, and more around the world. His strength is capturing life candidl
 y\, clearly\, and creatively. \n\nPalmer strives to tell stories in picture
 s about people and situations that might not otherwise be told\, with integ
 rity\, professionalism\, independence\, passion\, and compassion. \n\nPalme
 r’s photos have appeared in the New York Times\, BuzzFeed\, Narrative.ly\; 
 his writing in Smithsonian Magazine\, the New York Times\, and the Nation\;
  and Audio on Reveal.\n\n  Palmer’s documentary\, full disclosure\, which a
 ppeared in 2011 on the documentary channel\, along with several magazine ar
 ticles and photo exhibitions\, grew out of three media embeds in Iraq with 
 US marines. In 2019\, along with his collaborator\, Seth Wessler\, palmer r
 eceived a Peabody Award for the Reveal radio story “Monumental Lies.” \n\n 
 Before going freelance in 2002\, Palmer was a CNN correspondent. Prior to t
 hat\, he was Beijing Bureau Chief for US News & World Report\, during which
  time he photographed for many of his articles. \n\nPalmer collaborated wit
 h his wife\, Erin Hollaway Palmer\, on the documentary make the ground talk
  WHICH evokes life in a historic black community that was uprooted during W
 orld War II to build a naval base\, now a top-secret US military installati
 on. Palmer’s on-going project\, photography of Virginia’s neglected African
  American cemeteries\, grew out of the documentary.\n\nThe exhibit runs iun
 til May 20\, 2026.
DTEND:20260506T003000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215836Z
DTSTART:20260505T223000Z
GEO:35.907875;-79.050132
LOCATION:Sonja H Stone Center \, Brown Gallery & Museum \, 
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Gallery Exhibit Opening: "Making the Ground Talk and Other Stories"
  by Brian Palmer
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51835213941639
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/gallery-exhibit-opening-making-the-groun
 d-talk-and-other-stories-by-peabody-award-winning-photographer-and-journali
 st-brian-palmer
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Workshops and Classes
DESCRIPTION:Managing individuals who may be struggling with stress\, anxiet
 y\, depression and other mental health concerns can be a difficult balancin
 g act. Your role is to manage performance and to bring out the best in your
  workforce\, but accomplishing this often requires you to express concern a
 nd support when employees struggle emotionally. Managers often feel uncomfo
 rtable in this aspect of their role and may lack the important skills of “e
 motional management.” This course covers ways employees may present their d
 istress and offers insights and strategies on forging supportive empathic a
 lliances within the role of manager. The session also identifies common mis
 takes managers make in responding to employees in distress and explains com
 munication skills that express support and convey positive expectancy. Part
 icipants are also given information on how to refer employees to the Employ
 ee Assistance Program.\n\n \n\nWorkshop Objectives\nBy the end of this work
 shop\, you will:\n• Understand the universality of mental health issues in 
 the workplace\n• Recognize the most common symptoms of mental illness\n• Id
 entify the most common unhelpful reactions to symptoms\, why they occur and
  how to avoid them\n• Identify ways of expressing compassion and developing
  an alliance with distressed employees\n• Reduce the stigma associated ment
 al illness and promote ways of supporting one another in the workplace\n• R
 ecognize the warning signs of suicide\n• Identify support services and reso
 urces for all leaders and employees\n\n \n\nClick on Carolina Talent regist
 ration link and select the “Request” button to automatically enroll.
DTEND:20260506T170000Z
DTSTAMP:20260306T215836Z
DTSTART:20260506T160000Z
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Mental Health Awareness for Leaders
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51375462958731
URL:https://calendar.unc.edu/event/mental-health-awareness-for-leaders-7643
END:VEVENT
